data.body:
I have a very simple shader below that crashes when trying to set the WorldViewProjInv parameter due to an array overflow in ConstantBuffer.SetData (line 142). The constantbuffer size is reported at 48 when it should be 64.

Am I missing something ?

Here is the simplest shader that I could reproduce this with:

```
float4x4 WorldViewProjInv;

texture Cubemap;
samplerCUBE CubemapSampler = sampler_state
{
  Texture = <Cubemap>;
};

struct VertexShaderInput
{
    float4 Position : POSITION0;
};

struct VertexShaderOutput
{
    float4 Position : POSITION0;
    float3 TextureCoordinate0 : TEXCOORD0;
};

VertexShaderOutput VertexShaderFunction(VertexShaderInput input)
{
    VertexShaderOutput output;

    output.TextureCoordinate0 = mul(input.Position, WorldViewProjInv);
    output.Position = input.Position;

    return output;
}

float4 PixelShaderFunction(VertexShaderOutput input) : COLOR0
{
    return texCUBE(CubemapSampler, input.TextureCoordinate0);
}

technique Technique1
{
    pass Pass1
    {
        VertexShader = compile vs_2_0 VertexShaderFunction();
        PixelShader = compile ps_2_0 PixelShaderFunction();
    }
}
```

Works on HiDef profile on DirectX projects. Has a difference with XNA framework interface: instead of doing this:
_device.SetVertexBuffers(
 new VertexBufferBinding(vertexBuffer, 0, 0),
 new VertexBufferBinding(instanceBuffer, 0, 1)
);
you should do it like this:
_device.SetVertexBuffer(vertexBuffer);
_device.SetInstanceBuffer(instanceBuffer);

Other API parts of instancing is same as in XNA.

I'm pretty sure this line:
_graphicsDevice.PresentationParameters.IsFullScreen = false;

in GraphicsDeviceManager.Initialize() should read:
 _graphicsDevice.PresentationParameters.IsFullScreen = _wantFullScreen;

Which is the reason that setting the IsFullScreen property on creation of manager will not actually do anything until calling ToggleFullScreen() after the graphics device is already created.
